>Marine self inserts
You can write about what you know without writing a self-insert, but your problem has less to do with that and more to do with how self-aggrandizing it comes off. There are aviation themes in every single story I've written (with the notable exception of You Wouldn't Dare) because that's what I know, but none of those stories is a tour of of anon just generally being the best pilot ever, or even just about flying. For the parts that are, the great thing about writing about something you know is access to detail. I don't have to leave it at saying "anon went into a spin", I can describe what it feels like on the yoke, rudder, and in your stomach when you spin. That's what I want from your 240 gunning. I've sure as hell never fired a 240, much less in a combat situation, but you have. So tell me all the things about 240 gunning I'm not going to be able to pick up watching someone shoot one on youtube. Naa, bud. Good things, I really like the story. Even if its way outside my normal wheelhouse. In fact, you already showed some rabbit behavior of a bonded pair.

Bonded rabbits tend to spend most of their time together. Eating, sleeping, grooming each other. It can lead to a small amount of competitiveness over food but nothing large, mostly trying to get to food first. However grooming has a small amount of hierarchy to it. The top rabbit gets more grooming from its partner and shows that they want this by nudging the bottom bunny's chin with their head.

Female rabbits also tend to have a territory that they protect, even in a house. They show others to stay out with growling, and if someone continues they lunge at them with their front claws. Rabbits also sneeze if theirs dust in the air (although this could be size related) and if they encounter a smell they strongly dislike.

Rabbit contentment is easy to show but I'm unsure if it would really work in the story. It might so here I go. Rabbits have a very well know jump called a binky (its hard to describe, look it up on youtube.) as well aslaying on their side and lightly grinding their teeth if you pet them during this time.

Also, rabbits without companionship do have some problems that they typically suffer from. These include pulling out thier own fur durring grooming, overeating, and damaging their teeth.

Alright, that's enought for now. Sorry everyone with the wall of text, this kinda shit is fascinating to me.
